Dear Families,

     Thank you all for your thoughtfulness and caution as we do our best to
maintain safety, consistency, and routine for our children.  I know we=E2=
=80=99re
all feeling stressed, especially when plans for schools are still unknown.
I, as well as administration, will continue to be in communication as we
move forward.

     As of right now, schools seem to be scheduled to open on Monday.  If
you choose to keep your child home, please email Mia in the office at
mhernandez13@schools.nyc.gov.  She will make a note in school records that
the absence is related to Coronavirus.  At the bottom of this message,
you=E2=80=99ll find links for resources for math and literacy work if child=
ren are
staying home.  I will also be in touch with work beginning next week both
for children who stay home, and for all children, in the event that schools
close.

     All that said, we had a productive week in the classroom. The children
have been creating beautiful and imaginative poems, investigating ways to
make ten (and using some algebra), and diving into phonics work with
excitement.  Here is more about the week:



Poetry

     We have so many incredible poets in our class!  This week, we learned
that poems can be written about truly anything!  Topics this week ranged
from sharks to =E2=80=9Cgross stuff,=E2=80=9D from legos to dancing.  We=E2=
=80=99ve been working on
multiple drafts of poems-- which can be a tricky skill for first graders.
Reading and re-reading your work and thinking, =E2=80=9CDo I have a precise=
 word
for what I want to say?=E2=80=9D  =E2=80=9CDo my line breaks help my poem s=
ound musical?=E2=80=9D
and =E2=80=9CDoes my poem have meaning?=E2=80=9D We have been impressed wit=
h the work kids
are capable of in this regard, working and reworking poems to make them
just right!  Our first round of poems are on display outside the classroom.

Hair Love

     On Wednesday, we spent a few minutes watching the Oscar-nominated
short film based on the book Hair Love. We'd read the book last week as
part of our voting process for the Irma Black Book Award. Children were
quick to notice the differences between the book and the short film.  In
fact, the film had very little dialogue, so it posed an interesting
contrast to the story book.  The book is fantastic and the movie is
certainly worth 6 minutes of your time. Here=E2=80=99s the link if you=E2=
=80=99re
interested! <https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3DkNw8V_Fkw28>

Math This Week

     We=E2=80=99ve been playing so many math games that have to do with way=
s to
make 10.  We played =E2=80=9CTens Go Fish,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CCounters in a =
Cup=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9CShake and
Spill.=E2=80=9D

     We also worked on story problems that require some algebraic
thinking!  We encountered problems that posed, =E2=80=9CI have seven crayon=
s. Three
are blue. How many are red?=E2=80=9D  When reading the problem, we asked th=
e
questions,
=E2=80=9CWhat do I know?=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9CHow can I show what I know?=
=E2=80=9D

     Kids were prompted to draw a picture to represent their thinking and
write a number sentence with a blank for the missing information (e.g., 3
red + ___ blue =3D 7).  They had a few strategies for solving the problems.
Some kids turned the problem into a subtraction problem, knowing the fact
family (i.e., 7 - 3 =3D ?), while other kids rephrased the problem in their
minds by saying, =E2=80=9CIf I start at 3, how many more do I need to get t=
o 7?=E2=80=9D
This kind of reasoning was supported by the pictures they drew.

     I am sending along directions for both games.  For =E2=80=9CCounters i=
n a
Cup,=E2=80=9D you may use pennies as counters.  Both games could be adapted=
 to make
them more difficult or easier, as needed.  10 counters in a cup getting too
easy? Try 12, or 20!

Tens Go Fish <https://www.whatdowedoallday.com/easy-math-game-tens-go-fish/=
>

Counters in a Cup
<https://docs.google.com/document/d/1i_HTMiUC3WhBgrf4gbrO5_TGvKFAL72Lpga70e=
lKrKI/edit?usp=3Dsharing>

Blends and Digraphs

     What=E2=80=99s a digraph?  In a consonant digraph, two consonants stan=
d
together to represent a single sound.  the most common consonant digraphs
are: sh, ch, th, and wh. There are other consonant digraphs, but these are
the ones we are focusing on in first grade.

     A blend differs from a digraph in that the sounds are blended together
but remain two separate sounds.  For example, in the sp blend, we can
clearly hear the /s/ and /p/ sounds, whereas in the sh digraph, a new sound
/sh/ is created.

     In our shared reading we=E2=80=99ve been hunting for blends and digrap=
hs.
Kids have loved pointing them out, and are especially excited to notice
three letter blends (e.g., spl, str, spl).  Attached to this email is a
chart of blends and digraphs in case you want to do some "Spot the
Blend/Digraph" work at home.

